[Mikoyan Skat]] | Ship aircraft facilities = *Angled flight deck,<ref name="Janes 14May15"/> * with four launching positions (two ski-jump ramps and two electromagnetic catapults) * One set of arrestor gear. | Ship notes = dual island design<ref name="Janes 14May15"/> }} |} '''Project 23000E''' or '''Shtorm''' is a multi-purpose, [[Supercarrier|heavy aircraft carrier]] project being designed by the [[Krylov State Research Center]] for the [[Russian Navy]].<ref name="Janes 14May15">{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/51452/russia-developing-shtorm-supercarrier |title=Russia developing Shtorm supercarrier |author=Nikolai Novichkov |date=14 May 2015 |website=IHS Jane's Defence Weekly |accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref> The cost of the supercarrier is estimated as being between $1.8 billion and $5.63 billion (at August 2015 exchange rates), with development expected to take ten years. The carrier is being considered for service with the Russian Navy's [[Northern Fleet]]. [[Nevskoye Design Bureau]] is also reported to be taking part in the development project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Russia developing $5 bln aircraft carrier with no world analogs — fleet commander|url=http://tass.ru/en/russia/797980|website=TASS.RU|publisher=TASS|accessdate=7 August 2015}}</ref>
In July 2016, a Russian official confirmed that a delegation visiting [[India]] in early July had offered the design for India to purchase. <ref>[http://www.defensenews.com/story/defense/naval/navy/2016/07/11/russia-india-nuclear-aircraft-carrier-storm/86937106/ Russia Offers India Nuclear Aircraft Carrier], Vivek Raghuvanshi, [[Defense News]], 11 July 2016, accessed 19 July 2016</ref>
